CaseSummary.Summary:
The primary interest of this on-site investigation is the inflator rupture of a frontal air bag module and the fatal injuries to the driver in a 2001 Honda Civic that was involved in a frontal crash. This multi-vehicle crash occurred in September 2014 in the westbound lanes of a divided state highway in southern California. The Honda Civic was being driven by a belted 26-year-old female. There were three additional vehicles involved in this crash: a 2008 Honda Odyssey driven by a belted 50-year-old male with four passengers on board, a 2004 Nissan Murano driven by a belted 54-year-old male with three passengers on board, and a 2014 Mercedes-Benz GLK350 driven by a belted 35-year-old female with one passenger on board. All the vehicles were traveling in the third lane from the right at highway speeds. This was a chain-reaction type crash with the Honda Civic impacting the rear of the Honda Odyssey. The driver of the Honda Civic sustained a laceration to the left side of her neck. She was transported by ambulance to a local hospital. Upon arrival in the emergency room she went into full arrest. She was stabilized and then transported to a trauma center where she was treated and ultimately succumbed to her injuries. She was pronounced deceased at 2310 hours on the following day with the cause of death being a severe anoxic brain injury.
The driver of the Honda Civic sustained a laceration to the left side of her neck. She was transported by ambulance to a local hospital. Upon arrival in the emergency room she went into full arrest. She was stabilized and then transported to a trauma center where she was treated and ultimately succumbed to her injuries. She was pronounced deceased at 2310 hours on the following day with the cause of death being a severe anoxic brain injury. Police investigators indicated that the source of the neck injury was the vehicle safety belt. The belt was removed and placed into evidence. The belt was inspected at the police facility on June 19, 2015. In attendance during the inspection were representatives from Honda, Takata, NHTSA, the vehicle rental company, and attorneys associated with driver.
The drivers and occupants of the other vehicles were either not injured or reported minor complaints of pain and were not transported.
